  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "The legal history of money laundering prohibitions has evolved significantly over the past several decades:\n\n1. Early Origins:\n- Emerged as a concept in response to organized crime activities in the 1920s and 1930s\n- Initially focused on concealing proceeds from illegal activities like bootlegging and gambling\n\n2. Key Milestones:\n- 1970: Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) in the United States first established reporting requirements for financial transactions\n- 1986: Money Laundering Control Act in the US criminalized money laundering as a federal crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established to develop international anti-money laundering standards\n\n3. International Development:\n- 1988 UN Vienna Convention against drug trafficking\n- 1990 Council of Europe Convention on Laundering, Search, Seizure, and Confiscation of Proceeds\n- Gradual expansion of regulations to cover broader range of financial crimes\n\n4. Post-9/11 Developments:\n- USA PATRIOT Act dramatically expanded anti-money laundering (AML) regulations\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing prevention\n- Enhanced international cooperation and information sharing\n\n5. Contemporary Approach:\n- Comprehensive regulatory frameworks\n- Increased technological monitoring\n- Global coordination among financial institutions and law enforcement\n\nThis progression represents a complex legal evolution addressing increasingly sophisticated financial crimes.",
